# =============================================================================
# signing.properties.example – template for iOS release code-signing
# =============================================================================
#
# WHAT THIS IS
#   A template for the (git-ignored) file `ios/signing.properties`, which
#   supplies the Apple Developer Team ID to the `make release-ios` build. It is
#   the iOS counterpart of `android/keystore.properties` and is read the SAME
#   way: an environment variable wins, and the file is the fallback. The one
#   value it carries is the ten-character Team ID that Xcode's *automatic*
#   signing needs to pick the App-Store distribution certificate and
#   provisioning profile when the build runs head-less under xcodebuild.
#
# WHY IT IS NOT IN project.yml
#   `ios/project.yml` sets `DEVELOPMENT_TEAM: ""` under `settings.base` on
#   purpose: a value there is account-specific and would be committed, and a
#   non-empty `settings` value also OVERRIDES any xcconfig (see the comment in
#   project.yml), which would defeat the version generator. Keeping the Team ID
#   out of the tree entirely — here, next to the Play signing secrets — avoids
#   both problems. `make release-ios` injects the value as an xcodebuild
#   command-line build setting (`DEVELOPMENT_TEAM=…`), which takes precedence
#   over the empty project value for that one invocation, and also writes it as
#   the `teamID` of the generated ExportOptions.plist so the export step re-signs
#   with the right team.
#
# WHEN YOU NEED IT
#   ONLY for producing a SIGNED .ipa for App Store Connect / TestFlight via
#   `make release-ios` on a Mac. You do NOT need it for ordinary development
#   (the Simulator does not code-sign), for the container-runnable static checks,
#   or for any Android target. Without this file and without the environment
#   variable below, `make release-ios` stops early with an actionable message
#   rather than attempting an unsigned or mis-signed archive.
#
# HOW TO USE IT
#   1. Copy this file to `ios/signing.properties` (same directory, drop the
#      `.example` suffix). That copy is git-ignored and never committed.
#   2. Replace the placeholder below with your Team ID. You can read it from
#      Xcode (Settings → Accounts → your Apple ID → the team's 10-character ID)
#      or from the Apple Developer portal (Membership details → Team ID).
#   3. Run `make release-ios`. To override the file for a single build without
#      editing it, set the environment variable instead, e.g.
#      `DEVELOPMENT_TEAM=ABCDE12345 make release-ios` — the environment always
#      wins over the file, mirroring the Android keystore contract.
#
# The App Store Connect API key that the fastlane upload lanes use is a
# SEPARATE secret (the `.p8` referenced by the APP_STORE_CONNECT_API_KEY_*
# environment variables; see fastlane/Appfile and fastlane/Fastfile). This file
# is only about the code-signing Team ID for the local build.

# Your Apple Developer Team ID (10 characters, letters and digits).
DEVELOPMENT_TEAM=XXXXXXXXXX
